otnotes==\n{{reflist|group=N}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Liberalism|South Korea|Politics}}\n* [[Politics of South Korea]]\n* [[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2000)|Democratic Party]] (2000)\n* [[Democratic Party (South Korea, 2011)|Democratic Party]] (2011)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}} {{in lang|ko}}\n{{Democratic Party of Korea}}\n{{South Korean political parties}}\n\n[[Category:Minjoo Party of Korea| ]]\n[[Category:Liberal parties in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1955]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Social liberal parties]]\n[[Category:Nationalist parties in Asia]]\n[[Category:Korean nationalism]]\n", "name_user": "Marxistfounder", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Democratic_Party_of_Korea"}
{"title_page": "GlobalNxt University", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n|  name           = GlobalNxt University \n|  image          =  \n|  motto          = School for Global Leaders \n|  established    = June 2001 \n|  type           = [[Private school|Private]], [[For-Profit School|For-profit]] \n|  students       = 9,000+ \n|  city           = [[Kuala Lumpur]] \n|  country        = [[Malaysia]] \n|  website        = [http://www.globalnxt.edu.my/ Official site]\n}}\n'''GlobalNxt University''' (formerly '''Universitas 21 Global''' or '''U21Global''') is an accredited university with academic headquarters in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia. The university specialises primarily in management studies, and is a pioneer in the use of digital and educational technologies. Faculty of the university are located across the globe, as are the students. The university has strong partnerships with industry, developing an array of customised management development programmes for corporations. As of January 2013, U21Global had over 9,000 students from 72 countries.<ref name=\"DQMag\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dqmagazine.com/news/asias-newest-university-launches-online/ |title=Asia's Newest University Launches Online |publisher=Digital Quadrant |date=2013-01-04 |accessdate=2013-09-18}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:U21g.JPG|thumb|align=right|U21Global logo]]\nU21Global was formed in June 2001 in [[Singapore]] as a joint venture between [[Universitas 21]] and [[Thomson Learning]] (which later became [[Cengage Learning]]). Universitas 21 consisted of a network of high-profile universities including the Universities of Melbourne, Nottingham, Virginia and the National University of Singapore.\n\nIn late 2007, Cengage Learning sold its entire 50% in U21Global share to Mauritius-based Manipal Universal Learning International for an undisclosed sum.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.livemint.com/Companies/g9UsuulACmvLop2UTAR7oK/Manipal-group-buys-50-in-online-varsity.html |title=Manipal group buys 50% in online varsity |author=Staff Writer |newspaper=[[livemint]] |date=2007-11-14 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> In 2010, the Universitas 21 shareholding was diluted to 25 per cent, with only 10 universities continuing to hold equity.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/higher-education/manipal-to-control-u21global/story-e6frgcjx-1225823749309 |title=Manipal to Control U21Global |author=Trounson, Andrew |newspaper=[[The Australian]] |date=2010-01-27 |accessdate=2013-09-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, U21Global was invited by the Malaysia Ministry of Higher Education to re-stablish itself in Malaysia as part of the country's strategic drive to become a global educational hub. U21Global was re-established as GlobalNxt University, an accredited university in Malaysia with offices now based in [[Kuala Lumpur]], Malaysia.\n\n==Programmes==\nGlobalNxt University offers courses in [[Master of Business Administration]] (MBA), Postgraduate Diploma of Business Administration, [[Master of Science in Information Technology]] Management and Doctor of Business Administration (DBA).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/01/03/idUSnPre3BBBla+11c+PRN20130103 |title=GlobalNxt University, Asia's Newest University, Launches as Interest in Online Education Reaches New Highs |publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]] |date=2013-01-03| accessdate=2013-09-18}}</ref>  In Malaysia, all degree programmes must pass a rigorous external review before being granted full accreditation by the Malaysian Qualifications Agency.\n\nIn addition, the university developed a range of executive programmes in conjunction with industry partners.\n* Women's Leadership Programme (WLP)\n* Certificate in Global Business Leadership (CGBL)\n* Building Business Partnerships (BBP)\n* Sales Excellence Programme (SEP)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Thomson Learning]]\n*[[Cengage Learning]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.globalnxt.edu.my/}}\n\n{{Private universities in Malaysia}}\n\n[[Category:Malaysian educational websites]]\n[[Category:Sikkim Manipal University]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Kuala Lumpur]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2001]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Private universities in Malaysia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n|  name           = GlobalNxt University \n|  image          =  \n|  motto          = School for Global Leaders \n|  established    = June 2001 \n|  type           = [[Private school|Private]], [[For-Profit School|For-profit]] \n|  students       = 9,000+ \n|  city           = [[Kuala Lumpur]] \n|  country        = [[Malaysia]] \n|  website        = [http://www.globalnxt.edu.my/ Official site]\n}}\n'''GlobalNxt University''' (formerly '''Universitas 21 Global''' or '''U21Global''') is an accredited university with academic headquarters in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia. The university specialises primarily in management studies, and is a pioneer in the use of digital and educational technologies. Faculty of the university are located across the globe, as are the students. The university has strong partnerships with industry, developing an array of customised management development programmes for corporations. As of January 2013, U21Global had over 9,000 students from 72 countries.<ref name=\"DQMag\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dqmagazine.com/news/asias-newest-university-launches-online/ |title=Asia's Newest University Launches Online |publisher=Digital Quadrant |date=2013-01-04 |accessdate=2013-09-18}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:U21g.JPG|thumb|align=right|U21Global logo]]\nU21Global was formed in June 2001 in [[Singapore]] as a joint venture between [[Universitas 21]] and [[Thomson Learning]] (which later became [[Cengage Learning]]). Universitas 21 consisted of a network of high-profile universities including the Universities of Melbourne, Nottingham, Virginia and the National University of Singapore.\n\nIn late 2007, Cengage Learning sold its entire 50% in U21Global share to Mauritius-based Manipal Universal Learning International for an undisclosed sum.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.livemint.com/Companies/g9UsuulACmvLop2UTAR7oK/Manipal-group-buys-50-in-online-varsity.html |title=Manipal group buys 50% in online varsity |author=Staff Writer |newspaper=[[livemint]] |date=2007-11-14 |accessdate=2020-04-03}}</ref> In 2010, the Universitas 21 shareholding was diluted to 25 per cent, with only 10 universities continuing to hold equity.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/higher-education/manipal-to-control-u21global/story-e6frgcjx-1225823749309 |title=Manipal to Control U21Global |author=Trounson, Andrew |newspaper=[[The Australian]] |date=2010-01-27 |accessdate=2013-09-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, U21Global was invited by the Malaysia Ministry of Higher Education to re-stablish itself in Malaysia as part of the country's strategic drive to become a global educational hub. U21Global was re-established as GlobalNxt University, an accredited university in Malaysia with offices now based in [[Kuala Lumpur]], Malaysia.\n\n==Programmes==\nGlobalNxt University offers courses in [[Masters of Business Administration]] (MBA), Postgraduate Diploma of Business Administration, [[Master of Science in Information Technology]] Management and Doctor of Business Administration (DBA).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/01/03/idUSnPre3BBBla+11c+PRN20130103 |title=GlobalNxt University, Asia's Newest University, Launches as Interest in Online Education Reaches New Highs |publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]] |date=2013-01-03| accessdate=2013-09-18}}</ref>  In Malaysia, all degree programmes must pass a rigorous external review before being granted full accreditation by the Malaysian Qualifications Agency.\n\nIn addition, the university developed a range of executive programmes in conjunction with industry partners.\n* Women's Leadership Programme (WLP)\n* Certificate in Global Business Leadership (CGBL)\n* Building Business Partnerships (BBP)\n* Sales Excellence Programme (SEP)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Thomson Learning]]\n*[[Cengage Learning]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.globalnxt.edu.my/}}\n\n{{Private universities in Malaysia}}\n\n[[Category:Malaysian educational websites]]\n[[Category:Sikkim Manipal University]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Kuala Lumpur]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2001]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Private universities in Malaysia]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProgrammes:replaced: Masters \u2192 Master", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GlobalNxt_University"}
{"title_page": "Kevin Foreman", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Kevin Foreman\n| image        = \n| image_size   =\n| caption      =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1964|7|5|mf=y}} \n| birth_place  = Saskatchewan, Canada\n| alma_mater   = [[Harvard Business School]]\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| occupation   =  General Manager, GeoAnalytics, INRIX, Inc.. \n| net_worth    = \n| spouse       = Colette Foreman\n| children     = 4\n}}\n\n'''Kevin Foreman''' (born July 5, 1964) is the General Manager of GeoAnalytics at [[INRIX]]<ref name=rh_KevinForeman>{{cite web|url=http://techflash.com/seattle/2010/11/kevin-foreman-lands-at-inrix.html|title=Kevin Foreman lands at Inrix|date=November 24, 2010|publisher=TechFlash}}</ref> and former CEO of [[Point Inside]], a company that is 'mapping the indoor world'.<ref name=rh_Foremancooking>{{cite web|url=http://www.techflash.com/venture/Stealth_startup_of_the_week_Whats_Foreman_cooking_up_at__48273162.html|title=Stealth startup of the week: What's Foreman cooking up?|date=June 19, 2009|publisher=TechFlash}}</ref>  He founded Bevy, Inc. a [[Seattle]]-based company as entrepreneur-in-residence at [[Madrona Venture Group]] in September 2007.   Bevy received $1.2 million in funding from Madrona Venture Group and the [[Trilogy Partnership]] in October 2007.  Foreman described Bevy as a social merchandising venture and as \"a place where women can discuss and discover fashion from people they trust.\"<ref name=rh_fashioninsight>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/venture/366011_vc06.html|title=Venture Capital: Bevy lets women share fashion insight|date=June 5, 2008|publisher=Seattle Post Intelligencer}}</ref>\n\nHe used to be the General Manager of the Mobile Business Unit at [[RealNetworks]] Inc.  Earlier, he was Real's GM, [[Helix project|Helix]], and was credited with launching Real's [[Open-source model|open source]] strategy.\n\n==Education and career==\n\nHe was at [[RealNetworks]] from November 1997 to 2006.  His final role at RealNetworks was head of the mobile business unit.  He had headed the management of a digital media platform, [[Helix project|Helix]], and the industry ecosystem that builds on this platform, [[Helix Community]].   Prior to [[RealNetworks]], he worked for five years in various product and program management roles at [[Avid Technology]], the world's leading non-linear video-editing company.  Prior to Avid, he worked in various sales and sales management positions within [[Digital Equipment Corporation|DEC]].\n\nHe graduated from the [[University of Calgary]] with a Bachelor of Commerce degree.  He also earned a [[Master of Business Administration]] from the [[Harvard Business School]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foreman, Kevin}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Calgary alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Medicine Hat]]\n[[Category:American chief executives]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Kevin Foreman\n| image        = \n| image_size   =\n| caption      =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1964|7|5|mf=y}} \n| birth_place  = Saskatchewan, Canada\n| alma_mater   = [[Harvard Business School]]\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| occupation   =  General Manager, GeoAnalytics, INRIX, Inc.. \n| net_worth    = \n| spouse       = Colette Foreman\n| children     = 4\n}}\n\n'''Kevin Foreman''' (born July 5, 1964) is the General Manager of GeoAnalytics at [[INRIX]]<ref name=rh_KevinForeman>{{cite web|url=http://techflash.com/seattle/2010/11/kevin-foreman-lands-at-inrix.html|title=Kevin Foreman lands at Inrix|date=November 24, 2010|publisher=TechFlash}}</ref> and former CEO of [[Point Inside]], a company that is 'mapping the indoor world'.<ref name=rh_Foremancooking>{{cite web|url=http://www.techflash.com/venture/Stealth_startup_of_the_week_Whats_Foreman_cooking_up_at__48273162.html|title=Stealth startup of the week: What's Foreman cooking up?|date=June 19, 2009|publisher=TechFlash}}</ref>  He founded Bevy, Inc. a [[Seattle]]-based company as entrepreneur-in-residence at [[Madrona Venture Group]] in September 2007.   Bevy received $1.2 million in funding from Madrona Venture Group and the [[Trilogy Partnership]] in October 2007.  Foreman described Bevy as a social merchandising venture and as \"a place where women can discuss and discover fashion from people they trust.\"<ref name=rh_fashioninsight>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/venture/366011_vc06.html|title=Venture Capital: Bevy lets women share fashion insight|date=June 5, 2008|publisher=Seattle Post Intelligencer}}</ref>\n\nHe used to be the General Manager of the Mobile Business Unit at [[RealNetworks]] Inc.  Earlier, he was Real's GM, [[Helix project|Helix]], and was credited with launching Real's [[Open-source model|open source]] strategy.\n\n==Education and career==\n\nHe was at [[RealNetworks]] from November 1997 to 2006.  His final role at RealNetworks was head of the mobile business unit.  He had headed the management of a digital media platform, [[Helix project|Helix]], and the industry ecosystem that builds on this platform, [[Helix Community]].   Prior to [[RealNetworks]], he worked for five years in various product and program management roles at [[Avid Technology]], the world's leading non-linear video-editing company.  Prior to Avid, he worked in various sales and sales management positions within [[Digital Equipment Corporation|DEC]].\n\nHe graduated from the [[University of Calgary]] with a Bachelor of Commerce degree.  He also earned a [[Masters of Business Administration]] from the [[Harvard Business School]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foreman, Kevin}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Calgary alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Medicine Hat]]\n[[Category:American chief executives]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEducation and career:replaced: Masters \u2192 Master", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kevin_Foreman"}
{"title_page": "Lake Wales High School", "text_new": "{{Coord|27.9167|-81.5797|type:edu_region:US_FL|display=title}}\n{{Infobox School\n| name = Lake Wales High School\n| campus=[[Suburban]]\n| type = [[Charter school]]\n| grades = 9-12\n| principal = Donna Dunson \n| streetaddress = 1 Highlander Way\n| city = [[Lake Wales, Florida|Lake Wales]]\n| zipcode = 33853\n| state = [[Florida]]\n| country = United States of America\n| founded = 1921\n| motto = \n| slogan =\n| ratio = 19.10<ref name=NCES/>\n| staff = 82.00 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n| students = 1,566 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=1201590&SchoolPageNum=6&ID=120159001790|title=LAKE WALES SENIOR HIGH SCHOOL|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| faculty = 90\n| athletics = [[Florida High School Athletic Association]]\n| colors = {{color box|black}} [[Black]]<br/>{{color box|orange}} [[Orange (colour)|Orange]]\n| mascot = [[Scottish Highlanders|Highlanders]]\n| website = http://www.lakewaleshigh.com/\n}}\n\n'''Lake Wales High School''' is a high school located in [[Lake Wales]], [[Florida]], serving the city of Lake Wales and nearby communities such as [[Frostproof]], [[Florida]], [[Dundee]], [[Florida]] and [[Winter Haven, Florida|Winter Haven]], [[Florida]].\n==History==\nLake Wales served white students only until 1968, when Federally mandated integration required the school to take in 260 black students from Roosevelt High School, which was then repurposed as a junior high school.<ref name=\"Sentinel Due\">{{cite news |title=Roosevelt High Student Transfer Due This Year |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25379460/the-orlando-sentinel/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |via=newspapers.com |newspaper=Orlando Sentinel |date=July 25, 1968 |location=Orlando, Florida |page=58}}</ref>\n\n== Alumni ==\n* [[Pat Borders]] - Major League Baseball catcher 1988\u20132005, MVP of [[1992 World Series]] for [[Toronto Blue Jays]], Olympic gold medalist\n* [[Dominique Jones]] - pro basketball player\n* [[Rolan Milligan]] - football safety who is currently on the [[Detroit Lions]]\n*Thomas Wright - football strong safety, [[Michigan State]] (1999-2003), [[Tennessee Titans]] (2003-2005), [[Scottish Claymores]] (2004)\n*[[Wade Davis (baseball)|Wade Davis]] - [[Major League Baseball]] pitcher\n*[[Amare Stoudemire]] - [[NBA]] power forward and center (2002-2017), former [[NBA]] Rookie of the Year (2003)\n*Gervon Dexter- [[Florida Gators football]] Defensive Tackle 2021 present.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Polk County, Florida]]\n* [[Polk County Public Schools]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://lakewaleshigh.com/ Lake Wales High School Official Web Site]\n*[http://lwcharterschools.com/ Lake Wales Charter School System]\n*[http://www.cityoflakewales.com/ City of Lake Wales]\n\n{{Polk County, Florida Schools}}\n[[Category:High schools in Polk County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lake Wales, Florida]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Florida]]\n[[Category:Charter schools in Florida]]\n\n\n{{Florida-school-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Coord|27.9167|-81.5797|type:edu_region:US_FL|display=title}}\n{{Infobox School\n| name = Lake Wales High School\n| campus=[[Suburban]]\n| type = [[Charter school]]\n| grades = 9-12\n| principal = Donna Dunson \n| streetaddress = 1 Highlander Way\n| city = [[Lake Wales, Florida|Lake Wales]]\n| zipcode = 33853\n| state = [[Florida]]\n| country = United States of America\n| founded = 1921\n| motto = \n| slogan =\n| ratio = 19.10<ref name=NCES/>\n| staff = 82.00 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n| students = 1,566 (2017-18)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=1201590&SchoolPageNum=6&ID=120159001790|title=LAKE WALES SENIOR HIGH SCHOOL|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=November 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| faculty = 90\n| athletics = [[Florida High School Athletic Association]]\n| colors = {{color box|black}} [[Black]]<br/>{{color box|orange}} [[Orange (colour)|Orange]]\n| mascot = [[Scottish Highlanders|Highlanders]]\n| website = http://www.lakewaleshigh.com/\n}}\n\n'''Lake Wales High School''' is a high school located in [[Lake Wales]], [[Florida]], serving the city of Lake Wales and nearby communities such as [[Frostproof]], [[Florida]], [[Dundee]], [[Florida]] and [[Winter Haven, Florida|Winter Haven]], [[Florida]].\n==History==\nLake Wales served white students only until 1968, when Federally mandated integration required the school to take in 260 black students from Roosevelt High School, which was then repurposed as a junior high school.<ref name=\"Sentinel Due\">{{cite news |title=Roosevelt High Student Transfer Due This Year |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25379460/the-orlando-sentinel/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |via=newspapers.com |newspaper=Orlando Sentinel |date=July 25, 1968 |location=Orlando, Florida |page=58}}</ref>\n\n== Alumni ==\n* [[Pat Borders]] - Major League Baseball catcher 1988\u20132005, MVP of [[1992 World Series]] for [[Toronto Blue Jays]], Olympic gold medalist\n* [[Dominique Jones]] - pro basketball player\n* [[Rolan Milligan]] - football safety who is currently on the [[Detroit Lions]]\n*Thomas Wright - football strong safety, [[Michigan State]] (1999-2003), [[Tennessee Titans]] (2003-2005), [[Scottish Claymores]] (2004)\n*[[Wade Davis (baseball)|Wade Davis]] - [[Major League Baseball]] pitcher\n*[[Amare Stoudemire]] - [[NBA]] power forward and center (2002-2017), former [[NBA]] Rookie of the Year (2003)\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Polk County, Florida]]\n* [[Polk County Public Schools]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://lakewaleshigh.com/ Lake Wales High School Official Web Site]\n*[http://lwcharterschools.com/ Lake Wales Charter School System]\n*[http://www.cityoflakewales.com/ City of Lake Wales]\n\n{{Polk County, Florida Schools}}\n[[Category:High schools in Polk County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lake Wales, Florida]]\n[[Category:Public high schools in Florida]]\n[[Category:Charter schools in Florida]]\n\n\n{{Florida-school-stub}}\n", "name_user": "IsaacMlb24", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Wales_High_School"}
{"title_page": "Malay Archipelago", "text_new": "{{About|the archipelago|the book|The Malay Archipelago}}\n{{Coord|2|56|S|107|55|E|type:isle_source:kolossus-ruwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Infobox islands\n|name = Malay Archipelago\n|image_name = Location Malay Archipelago.png\n|image_caption = World map highlighting Malay Archipelago\n|location = [[Maritime Southeast Asia]], [[Melanesia]]\n|coordinates = \n|area_km2 = 2000000\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"area\">{{cite book |last1=Moores |first1=Eldridge M. |last2=Fairbridge |first2=Rhodes Whitmore |author1-link=Eldridge M. Moores |author2-link=Rhodes Fairbridge |title=Encyclopedia of European and Asian regional geology |url=https://books.google.com/?id=aYRup5mRcGsC&pg=PA377&dq=%22malay+archipelago%22+2+million+km%C2%B2#v=onepage&q= |page=377|accessdate=30 November 2009 |year=1997 |publisher=Springer |isbn=0-412-74040-0 }}</ref>\n|total_islands = 25,000\n|major_islands = [[Borneo]], [[Java]], [[Luzon]], [[Mindanao]], [[New Guinea]], [[Sulawesi]], [[Sumatra]]\n|highest_mount = \n|elevation_m = \n|country = {{flag|Brunei}}\n|country_largest_city = [[Bandar Seri Begawan]]\n|country1 = {{flagicon|Malaysia}} [[East Malaysia]]\n|country1_largest_city = [[Kuching]]\n|country2 = {{flag|East Timor}}\n|country2_largest_city = [[Dili]]\n|country3 = {{flag|Indonesia}}\n|country3_largest_city = [[Jakarta]]\n|country4 = {{flag|Papua New Guinea}}\n|country4_largest_city = [[Port Moresby]]\n|country5 = {{flag|Philippines}}\n|country5_largest_city = [[Quezon City]]\n|density_km2 = \n|population = 380,000,000\n|population_footnotes = <ref name=unpop>{{Cite journal | url=https://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/wpp2006/WPP2006_Highlights_rev.pdf | title=World Population Prospects, Table A.2| version=2006 revision | pages=37\u201342  | format=[[PDF]] | publisher=United Nations | author=Department of Economic and Social Affairs Population Division | year=2006 | accessdate= 2007-06-30}}</ref>\n|ethnic_groups = Predominantly [[Austronesian peoples|Austronesians]], with minorities of [[Negritos]], [[Papuan peoples|Papuans]], [[Melanesians]], [[Overseas Chinese]], [[Arab Indonesians|Arabs descendants]], and [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|Overseas Indians]]\n|}}\n\nThe '''Malay Archipelago''' ({{lang-ms|Kepulauan Melayu}}, {{lang-tgl|Kapuluang Malay}}, [[Visayan languages|Visayan]]: ''Kapupud-ang Malay'') is the [[archipelago]] between mainland [[Mainland Southeast Asia|Indochina]] and [[Australia (continent)|Australia]]. It has also been called the '''[[Malay world]]''', '''[[Nusantara]]''', '''[[East Indies]]''', '''Indo-Australian Archipelago''', '''Spices Archipelago''' and other names over time. The name was taken from the 19th-century European concept of a [[Malay race]], later based on the distribution of [[Austronesian languages]].<ref name=Wallace>{{Cite book  | last = Wallace  | first = Alfred Russel  | authorlink = Alfred Russel Wallace | title = The Malay Archipelago | publisher = Macmillan and Co  | year = 1869  | location = London  | page = 1 }}</ref><!--Wallace uses the term, the 'Malay race,' but does not say it was anachronistic.-->\n\nSituated between the [[Indian Ocean|Indian]] and [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific Oceans]], the archipelago of over 25,000 [[island]]s and islets is the largest [[archipelago]] by area and fourth by [[list of archipelagos by number of islands|number of islands]] in the [[world]]. It includes [[Brunei]], [[East Malaysia]], [[East Timor]], [[Indonesia]], [[Papua New Guinea]], and the [[Philippines]].<ref name= Britannica>''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''.  2006.  Chicago: Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.</ref><ref>[https://www.britannica.com/place/Malay-Archipelago Encyclopaedia Britannica \u2013 Malay Archipelago]</ref> The term is largely synonymous with [[Maritime Southeast Asia]].<ref name=Worldworx>\"[http://www.worldworx.tv/regional-information/asia/maritime-southeast-asia/index.htm Maritime Southeast Asia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070613061856/http://www.worldworx.tv/regional-information/asia/maritime-southeast-asia/index.htm |date=2007-06-13 }}.\" ''Worldworx Travel''.  Accessed 26 May 2009.</ref>\n\n== Etymology and terminology ==\nThe term was derived from the European concept of a \"[[Malay race]]\" (the [[Austronesian peoples]]),<ref name=Wallace/> a racial concept proposed by [[Europe|European]] explorers based on their observations of the influence of the [[Malays (ethnic group)|ethnic Malay]] empire, [[Srivijaya]], which was based on the island of [[Sumatra]], [[Indonesia]].<ref>Reid, Anthony. [http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-2067345_ITM ''Understanding Melayu (Malay) as a Source of Diverse Modern Identities. Origins of Malayness''], Cambridge University Press, 2001. Retrieved on March 2, 2009.</ref> However, the Malay Archipelago does not include all islands inhabited by the Malay race such as [[Madagascar]] and [[Taiwan]], and it includes the islands inhabited by [[Melanesians]] such as [[Maluku Islands]] and [[New Guinea]].\n[[File:Sea Safari VII, Komodo, 2016 (04).jpg|thumb|left|[[Pinisi]] sailing ship exploring [[Komodo (island)|Komodo island]], part of [[Lesser Sunda Islands]]]]\nThe 19th-century naturalist [[Alfred Russel Wallace|Alfred Wallace]] used the term \"Malay Archipelago\" as the title of [[The Malay Archipelago|his influential book]] documenting his studies in the region. Wallace also referred to the area as the \"Indian Archipelago\" and the \"Indo-Australian\" Archipelago.<ref>{{cite web\n |last=Wallace \n |first=Alfred Russel \n |authorlink=Alfred Russel Wallace \n |title=On the Physical Geography of the Malay Archipelago \n |url=http://web2.wku.edu/~smithch/wallace/S078.htm \n |year=1863 \n |accessdate=30 November 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117084201/http://web2.wku.edu/~smithch/wallace/S078.htm \n |archivedate=17 January 2010 \n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last = Wallace | first = Alfred Russel | authorlink = Alfred Russel Wallace | title = The Malay Archipelago | publisher = Macmillan and Co | year = 1869 | location = London | page = 2 }}</ref> He included within the region the [[Solomon Islands]] and the [[Malay Peninsula]] due to physiographic similarities.<ref name=Wallace /> As Wallace noted,<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.papuaweb.org/dlib/bk/wallace/race.html|chapter=40: The Races of Man in the Malay Archipelago|website=papuaweb.org|title=The Malay Archipelago|date=1869|first=Alfred Russel|last=Wallace|authorlink=Alfred Russel Wallace|access-date=2009-08-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016195922/http://www.papuaweb.org/dlib/bk/wallace/race.html|archive-date=2012-10-16|url-status=dead}}\n<blockquote>\"If we draw a line ... commencing along the western coast of Gilolo, through the island of Bouru, and curving round the west end of Mores, then bending back by Sandalwood Island to take in Rotti, we shall divide the Archipelago into two portions, the races of which have strongly marked distinctive peculiarities. This line will separate the Malayan and all the Asiatic races, from the Papuans and all that inhabit the Pacific; and though along the line of junction intermigration and commixture have taken place, yet the division is on the whole almost as well defined and strongly contrasted, as is the corresponding zoological division of the Archipelago, into an Indo-Malayan and Austro-Malayan region.\"</ref> there are arguments for excluding [[Papua New Guinea]] for cultural and geographical reasons: Papua New Guinea is culturally quite different from the other countries in the region, and it is geologically not part of the continent of [[Asia]], as the islands of the [[Sunda Shelf]] are (see [[Australia (continent)|Australia]]).\n\nThe archipelago was called the \"[[East Indies]]\"<ref>[[Oxford English Dictionary|OED first edition]] ''A geographical term, including Hindostan, Further India, and the islands beyond'' with first found usage 1598</ref> from the late 16th century and throughout the European colonial era. It is still sometimes referred to as such,<ref name=Britannica /> but broader usages of the \"East Indies\" term had included [[mainland Southeast Asia|Indochina]] and the [[Indian subcontinent]]. The area is called \"[[Nusantara]]\" in the [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]] language.<ref>{{Cite book\n| last = Echols  | first = John M. | last2 = Shadily | first2 = Hassan  | author2-link =   | title = Kamus Indonesia Inggris (An Indonesian-English Dictionary) | place = Jakarta  | publisher = Gramedia  | year = 1989|edition=1st | isbn = 979-403-756-7}}; {{cite book |last1=Moores |first1=Eldridge M. |last2=Fairbridge |first2=Rhodes Whitmore |author1-link=Eldridge M. Moores |author2-link=Rhodes Fairbridge |title=Encyclopedia of European and Asian regional geology |url=https://books.google.com/?id=aYRup5mRcGsC&pg=PA377&dq=%22malay+archipelago%22+2+million+km%C2%B2#v=onepage&q= |page=377|accessdate=30 November 2009 |year=1997 |publisher=Springer |isbn=0-412-74040-0 }}</ref> The area is also referred to as the \"Indonesian archipelago\".<ref>Friedhelm G\u00f6ltenboth (2006) ''Ecology of insular Southeast Asia: the Indonesian Archipelago'' Elsevier,  {{ISBN|0-444-52739-7}}, {{ISBN|978-0-444-52739-4}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ikSQw_-8gboC&pg=PA227&dq=maritime+southeast+asia&ei=q9olS730OZOkkATG58nOCw&cd=1#v=onepage&q=malay%20archipelago&f=false ''Modern Quaternary Research in Southeast Asia,'' Volume 1]</ref> The term \"[[Maritime Southeast Asia]]\" is largely synonymous, covering both the islands in Southeast Asia and nearby island-like communities, such as those found on the [[Malay Peninsula]].<ref>{{cite book\n|last=Shaffer\n|first=Lynda\n|title=Maritime Southeast Asia to 1500\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X58tqsLz0dIC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Maritime+Southeast+Asia+to+1500#v=onepage&q=&f=false\n|year=1996\n|publisher=M.E. Sharpe\n|page=xi\n|isbn=1-56324-144-7}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:Philippines Bohol Virgin Island.JPG|thumb|One of the majority of uninhabited islands of the [[Philippines]].]]\n\nThe land and sea area of the archipelago exceeds 2 million km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=\"area\" /> The more than 25,000 islands of the archipelago comprise many smaller archipelagoes.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071022221129/http://www.gov.ph/aboutphil/general.asp Philippines : General Information]. Government of the Philippines. Retrieved 2009-11-06; {{cite press release|publisher=[[International Monetary Fund]] |url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2006/01/data/dbcoutm.cfm?SD=2005&ED=2005&R1=1&R2=1&CS=3&SS=2&OS=C&DD=0&OUT=1&C=536&S=PPPWGT-PPPPC&RequestTimeout=120&CMP=0&x=45&y=5 |accessdate=2006-10-05 |title=World Economic Outlook Database |date=April 2006 }}; {{cite web|title=Indonesia Regions |publisher=Indonesia Business Directory |url=http://www.indonext.com/Regions/ |accessdate=2007-04-24 }}</ref>\n\nThe major groupings are:\n\n* [[List of islands of Indonesia|Indonesian Archipelago]]\n** [[Maluku Islands]]\n** [[New Guinea]]\n** [[Sunda Islands]]\n*** [[Greater Sunda Islands]]\n**** [[Borneo]]\n**** [[Java]]\n**** [[Sulawesi]]\n**** [[Sumatra]]\n*** [[Lesser Sunda Islands]]\n**** [[Alor Archipelago]]\n**** [[Bali]]\n**** [[Barat Daya Islands]]\n**** [[Flores]]\n**** [[Komodo (island)|Komodo]]\n**** [[Lombok]]\n**** [[Sumba]]\n**** [[Sumbawa]]\n**** [[Tanimbar Islands]]\n**** [[Timor]]\n* [[List of islands of the Philippines|Philippine Archipelago]]\n** [[Luzon]]\n** [[Mindanao]]\n** [[Visayas|Visayan Islands]]\n\nThe seven largest islands are [[New Guinea]], [[Borneo]], [[Sumatra]], [[Sulawesi]] and [[Java]] in Indonesia; and [[Luzon]] and [[Mindanao]] in the Philippines.\n\nGeologically, the archipelago is one of the most active [[volcano|volcanic]] regions in the world. Producing many [[List of volcanoes in Indonesia| volcanoes especially in Java, Sumatra and Lesser Sunda Islands region]] where most volcanoes over {{convert|3000|m|0|abbr=on}} situated. [[Tectonic uplift]]s also produced large mountains, including the highest in [[Mount Kinabalu]] in [[Sabah]], Malaysia, with a height of 4,095.2&nbsp;m and [[Puncak Jaya]] on Papua, Indonesia at {{convert|4884|m|0|abbr=on}}. Other high mountains in the archipelago include [[Puncak Mandala]], Indonesia at {{convert|4760|m|0|abbr=on}} and [[Puncak Trikora]], Indonesia, at {{convert|4750|m|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe climate throughout the archipelago is tropical, owing to its position on the [[equator]].\n\n=== Biogeography ===\n[[File:L\u00ednea de Wallace.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|[[Wallace's line]] between Australian and Southeast Asian fauna. The deep water of the Lombok Strait between the islands of Bali and Lombok formed a water barrier even when lower sea levels linked the now-separated islands and landmasses on either side.]]\n\nWallace used the term [[The Malay Archipelago|''Malay Archipelago'']] as the title of his influential book documenting his studies in the region. He proposed what would come to be known as the \"[[Wallace Line]]\", a boundary that separated the flora and fauna of Asia and Australia. The ice age boundary was formed by the deep water straits between [[Borneo]] and [[Sulawesi]]; and through the [[Lombok Strait]] between [[Bali]] and [[Lombok]]. This is now considered the western border of the [[Wallacea]] transition zone between the [[Ecozone|zoogeographical regions]] of Asia and Australia. The zone has a mixture of species of Asian and Australian origin, and its own endemic species.\n\n== Demography ==\n{{See also|Southeast Asia#Demographics}}\n\nOver 380 million people live in the region, with the 10 most populated islands being the following:\n\n# [[Java]] (141,000,000)\n# [[Sumatra]] (50,180,000)\n# [[Luzon]] (48,520,774)\n# [[Mindanao]] (21,902,000)\n# [[Borneo]] (21,258,000)\n# [[Sulawesi]] (21,258,000)\n# [[New Guinea]] (11,306,940)\n# [[Singapore]] (5,638,700)\n# [[Negros Island|Negros]] (4,414,131)\n# [[Panay]] (4,302,634)\n\nThe people living there are predominantly from [[Austronesian peoples|Austronesian]] sub-groupings and correspondingly speak western [[Malayo-Polynesian languages]]. The main religions in this region are [[Islam]], [[Christianity]], [[Buddhism]], [[Hinduism]] and traditional [[animism]].\n\nCulturally, the region is often seen{{Who|date=June 2011}} as part of \"Farther India\" or [[Greater India]]\u2014the Coedes' ''Indianized states of Southeast Asia'' refers to it as \"Island Southeast Asia\".<ref>Coedes, G. (1968) ''The Indianized states of Southeast Asia'' Edited by Walter F. Vella. Translated by Susan Brown Cowing.Canberra : Australian National University Press. Introduction... ''The geographic area here called ''Farther India'' consists of Indonesia, or island Southeast Asia....''</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col|small=yes}}\n*[[Greater Indonesia]]\n*[[Insulindia]]\n*[[Malay Peninsula]]\n*[[Malayness]]\n*[[Maphilindo]]\n*[[Maritime Southeast Asia]]\n*[[Nusantara]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [[Alfred Russel Wallace|Wallace, Alfred Russel]]. ''The Malay Archipelago'', [http://www.authorama.com/book/malay-archipelago-1.html Volume I], [http://www.authorama.com/book/malay-archipelago-2.html, Volume II].\n* [http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/42850/rec/1 Art of Island Southeast Asia], full-text of an exhibition catalog from the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\n\n{{Countries of the Malay Archipelago}}\n{{Regions of the world}}\n\n[[Category:Malaya| 01]]\n[[Category:Islands of Southeast Asia]]\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Southeast Asia]]\n[[Category:Maritime Southeast Asia|*]]\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of the Indian Ocean]]\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:International archipelagoes]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the archipelago|the book|The Malay Archipelago}}\n{{Coord|2|56|S|107|55|E|type:isle_source:kolossus-ruwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Infobox islands\n|name = Malay Archipelago\n|image_name = Location Malay Archipelago.png\n|image_caption = World map highlighting Malay Archipelago\n|location = [[Maritime Southeast Asia]], [[Melanesia]]\n|coordinates = \n|area_km2 = 2000000\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"area\">{{cite book |last1=Moores |first1=Eldridge M. |last2=Fairbridge |first2=Rhodes Whitmore |author1-link=Eldridge M. Moores |author2-link=Rhodes Fairbridge |title=Encyclopedia of European and Asian regional geology |url=https://books.google.com/?id=aYRup5mRcGsC&pg=PA377&dq=%22malay+archipelago%22+2+million+km%C2%B2#v=onepage&q= |page=377|accessdate=30 November 2009 |year=1997 |publisher=Springer |isbn=0-412-74040-0 }}</ref>\n|total_islands = 25,000\n|major_islands = [[Borneo]], [[Java]], [[Luzon]], [[Mindanao]], [[New Guinea]], [[Sulawesi]], [[Sumatra]]\n|highest_mount = \n|elevation_m = \n|country = {{flag|Brunei}}\n|country_largest_city = [[Bandar Seri Begawan]]\n|country1 = {{flagicon|Malaysia}} [[East Malaysia]]\n|country1_largest_city = [[Kuching]]\n|country2 = {{flag|East Timor}}\n|country2_largest_city = [[Dili]]\n|country3 = {{flag|Indonesia}}\n|country3_largest_city = [[Jakarta]]\n|country4 = {{flag|Papua New Guinea}}\n|country4_largest_city = [[Port Moresby]]\n|country5 = {{flag|Philippines}}\n|country5_largest_city = [[Quezon City]]\n|density_km2 = \n|population = 380,000,000\n|population_footnotes = <ref name=unpop>{{Cite journal | url=https://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/wpp2006/WPP2006_Highlights_rev.pdf | title=World Population Prospects, Table A.2| version=2006 revision | pages=37\u201342  | format=[[PDF]] | publisher=United Nations | author=Department of Economic and Social Affairs Population Division | year=2006 | accessdate= 2007-06-30}}</ref>\n|ethnic_groups = Predominantly [[Austronesian peoples|Austronesians]], with minorities of [[Negritos]], [[Papuan peoples|Papuans]], [[Melanesians]], [[Overseas Chinese]], [[Arab Indonesians|Arabs descendants]], and [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|Overseas Indians]]\n|}}\n\nThe '''Malay Archipelago''' ({{lang-ms|Kepulauan Melayu}}, {{lang-tgl|Kapuluang Malay}}, [[Visayan languages|Visayan]]: ''Kapupud-ang Malay'') is the [[archipelago]] between mainland [[Mainland Southeast Asia|Indochina]] and [[Australia (continent)|Australia]]. It has also been called the '''[[Malay world]]''', '''[[Nusantara]]''', '''[[East Indies]]''', '''Indo-Australian Archipelago''', '''Spices Archipelago''' and other names over time. The name was taken from the 19th-century European concept of a [[Malay race]], later based on the distribution of [[Austronesian languages]].<ref name=Wallace>{{Cite book  | last = Wallace  | first = Alfred Russel  | authorlink = Alfred Russel Wallace | title = The Malay Archipelago | publisher = Macmillan and Co  | year = 1869  | location = London  | page = 1 }}</ref><!--Wallace uses the term, the 'Malay race,' but does not say it was anachronistic.-->\n\nSituated between the [[Indian Ocean|Indian]] and [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific Oceans]], the archipelago of over 25,000 [[island]]s and islets is the largest [[archipelago]] by area and fourth by [[list of archipelagos by number of islands|number of islands]] in the [[world]]. It includes [[Brunei]], [[East Malaysia]], [[East Timor]], [[Indonesia]], [[Papua New Guinea]], and the [[Philippines]].<ref name= Britannica>''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''.  2006.  Chicago: Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.</ref><ref>[https://www.britannica.com/place/Malay-Archipelago Encyclopaedia Britannica \u2013 Malay Archipelago]</ref> The term is largely synonymous with [[Maritime Southeast Asia]].<ref name=Worldworx>\"[http://www.worldworx.tv/regional-information/asia/maritime-southeast-asia/index.htm Maritime Southeast Asia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070613061856/http://www.worldworx.tv/regional-information/asia/maritime-southeast-asia/index.htm |date=2007-06-13 }}.\" ''Worldworx Travel''.  Accessed 26 May 2009.</ref>\n\n== Etymology and terminology ==\nThe term was derived from the European concept of a \"[[Malay race]]\" (the [[Austronesian peoples]]),<ref name=Wallace/> a racial concept proposed by [[Europe|European]] explorers based on their observations of the influence of the [[Malays (ethnic group)|ethnic Malay]] empire, [[Srivijaya]], which was based on the island of [[Sumatra]], [[Indonesia]].<ref>Reid, Anthony. [http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-2067345_ITM ''Understanding Melayu (Malay) as a Source of Diverse Modern Identities. Origins of Malayness''], Cambridge University Press, 2001. Retrieved on March 2, 2009.</ref> However, the Malay Archipelago does not include all islands inhabited by the Malay race such as [[Madagascar]] and [[Taiwan]], and it includes the islands inhabited by [[Melanesians]] such as [[Maluku Islands]] and [[New Guinea]].\n[[File:Sea Safari VII, Komodo, 2016 (04).jpg|thumb|left|[[Pinisi]] sailing ship exploring [[Komodo (island)|Komodo island]], part of [[Lesser Sunda Islands]]]]\nThe 19th-century naturalist [[Alfred Russel Wallace|Alfred Wallace]] used the term \"Malay Archipelago\" as the title of [[The Malay Archipelago|his influential book]] documenting his studies in the region. Wallace also referred to the area as the \"Indian Archipelago\" and the \"Indo-Australian\" Archipelago.<ref>{{cite web\n |last=Wallace \n |first=Alfred Russel \n |authorlink=Alfred Russel Wallace \n |title=On the Physical Geography of the Malay Archipelago \n |url=http://web2.wku.edu/~smithch/wallace/S078.htm \n |year=1863 \n |accessdate=30 November 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117084201/http://web2.wku.edu/~smithch/wallace/S078.htm \n |archivedate=17 January 2010 \n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last = Wallace | first = Alfred Russel | authorlink = Alfred Russel Wallace | title = The Malay Archipelago | publisher = Macmillan and Co | year = 1869 | location = London | page = 2 }}</ref> He included within the region the [[Solomon Islands]] and the [[Malay Peninsula]] due to physiographic similarities.<ref name=Wallace /> As Wallace noted,<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.papuaweb.org/dlib/bk/wallace/race.html|chapter=40: The Races of Man in the Malay Archipelago|website=papuaweb.org|title=The Malay Archipelago|date=1869|first=Alfred Russel|last=Wallace|authorlink=Alfred Russel Wallace|access-date=2009-08-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016195922/http://www.papuaweb.org/dlib/bk/wallace/race.html|archive-date=2012-10-16|url-status=dead}}\n<blockquote>\"If we draw a line ... commencing along the western coast of Gilolo, through the island of Bouru, and curving round the west end of Mores, then bending back by Sandalwood Island to take in Rotti, we shall divide the Archipelago into two portions, the races of which have strongly marked distinctive peculiarities. This line will separate the Malayan and all the Asiatic races, from the Papuans and all that inhabit the Pacific; and though along the line of junction intermigration and commixture have taken place, yet the division is on the whole almost as well defined and strongly contrasted, as is the corresponding zoological division of the Archipelago, into an Indo-Malayan and Austro-Malayan region.\"</ref> there are arguments for excluding [[Papua New Guinea]] for cultural and geographical reasons: Papua New Guinea is culturally quite different from the other countries in the region, and it is geologically not part of the continent of [[Asia]], as the islands of the [[Sunda Shelf]] are (see [[Australia (continent)|Australia]]).\n\nThe archipelago was called the \"[[East Indies]]\"<ref>[[Oxford English Dictionary|OED first edition]] ''A geographical term, including Hindostan, Further India, and the islands beyond'' with first found usage 1598</ref> from the late 16th century and throughout the European colonial era. It is still sometimes referred to as such,<ref name=Britannica /> but broader usages of the \"East Indies\" term had included [[mainland Southeast Asia|Indochina]] and the [[Indian subcontinent]]. The area is called \"[[Nusantara]]\" in the [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]] language.<ref>{{Cite book\n| last = Echols  | first = John M. | last2 = Shadily | first2 = Hassan  | author2-link =   | title = Kamus Indonesia Inggris (An Indonesian-English Dictionary) | place = Jakarta  | publisher = Gramedia  | year = 1989|edition=1st | isbn = 979-403-756-7}}; {{cite book |last1=Moores |first1=Eldridge M. |last2=Fairbridge |first2=Rhodes Whitmore |author1-link=Eldridge M. Moores |author2-link=Rhodes Fairbridge |title=Encyclopedia of European and Asian regional geology |url=https://books.google.com/?id=aYRup5mRcGsC&pg=PA377&dq=%22malay+archipelago%22+2+million+km%C2%B2#v=onepage&q= |page=377|accessdate=30 November 2009 |year=1997 |publisher=Springer |isbn=0-412-74040-0 }}</ref> The area is also referred to as the \"Indonesian archipelago\".<ref>Friedhelm G\u00f6ltenboth (2006) ''Ecology of insular Southeast Asia: the Indonesian Archipelago'' Elsevier,  {{ISBN|0-444-52739-7}}, {{ISBN|978-0-444-52739-4}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ikSQw_-8gboC&pg=PA227&dq=maritime+southeast+asia&ei=q9olS730OZOkkATG58nOCw&cd=1#v=onepage&q=malay%20archipelago&f=false ''Modern Quaternary Research in Southeast Asia,'' Volume 1]</ref> The term \"[[Maritime Southeast Asia]]\" is largely synonymous, covering both the islands in Southeast Asia and nearby island-like communities, such as those found on the [[Malay Peninsula]].<ref>{{cite book\n|last=Shaffer\n|first=Lynda\n|title=Maritime Southeast Asia to 1500\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X58tqsLz0dIC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Maritime+Southeast+Asia+to+1500#v=onepage&q=&f=false\n|year=1996\n|publisher=M.E. Sharpe\n|page=xi\n|isbn=1-56324-144-7}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:Philippines Bohol Virgin Island.JPG|thumb|One of the majority of uninhabited islands of the [[Philippines]].]]\n\nThe land and sea area of the archipelago exceeds 2 million km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=\"area\" /> The more than 25,000 islands of the archipelago comprise many smaller archipelagoes.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071022221129/http://www.gov.ph/aboutphil/general.asp Philippines : General Information]. Government of the Philippines. Retrieved 2009-11-06; {{cite press release|publisher=[[International Monetary Fund]] |url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2006/01/data/dbcoutm.cfm?SD=2005&ED=2005&R1=1&R2=1&CS=3&SS=2&OS=C&DD=0&OUT=1&C=536&S=PPPWGT-PPPPC&RequestTimeout=120&CMP=0&x=45&y=5 |accessdate=2006-10-05 |title=World Economic Outlook Database |date=April 2006 }}; {{cite web|title=Indonesia Regions |publisher=Indonesia Business Directory |url=http://www.indonext.com/Regions/ |accessdate=2007-04-24 }}</ref>\n\nThe major groupings are:\n\n* [[List of islands of Indonesia|Indonesian Archipelago]]\n** [[Maluku Islands]]\n** [[New Guinea]]\n** [[Sunda Islands]]\n*** [[Greater Sunda Islands]]\n**** [[Borneo]]\n**** [[Java]]\n**** [[Sulawesi]]\n**** [[Sumatra]]\n*** [[Lesser Sunda Islands]]\n**** [[Alor Archipelago]]\n**** [[Bali]]\n**** [[Barat Daya Islands]]\n**** [[Flores]]\n**** [[Lombok]]\n**** [[Sumba]]\n**** [[Sumbawa]]\n**** [[Tanimbar Islands]]\n**** [[Timor]]\n* [[List of islands of the Philippines|Philippine Archipelago]]\n** [[Luzon]]\n** [[Mindanao]]\n** [[Visayas|Visayan Islands]]\n\nThe seven largest islands are [[New Guinea]], [[Borneo]], [[Sumatra]], [[Sulawesi]] and [[Java]] in Indonesia; and [[Luzon]] and [[Mindanao]] in the Philippines.\n\nGeologically, the archipelago is one of the most active [[volcano|volcanic]] regions in the world. Producing many [[List of volcanoes in Indonesia| volcanoes especially in Java, Sumatra and Lesser Sunda Islands region]] where most volcanoes over {{convert|3000|m|0|abbr=on}} situated. [[Tectonic uplift]]s also produced large mountains, including the highest in [[Mount Kinabalu]] in [[Sabah]], Malaysia, with a height of 4,095.2&nbsp;m and [[Puncak Jaya]] on Papua, Indonesia at {{convert|4884|m|0|abbr=on}}. Other high mountains in the archipelago include [[Puncak Mandala]], Indonesia at {{convert|4760|m|0|abbr=on}} and [[Puncak Trikora]], Indonesia, at {{convert|4750|m|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe climate throughout the archipelago is tropical, owing to its position on the [[equator]].\n\n=== Biogeography ===\n[[File:L\u00ednea de Wallace.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|[[Wallace's line]] between Australian and Southeast Asian fauna. The deep water of the Lombok Strait between the islands of Bali and Lombok formed a water barrier even when lower sea levels linked the now-separated islands and landmasses on either side.]]\n\nWallace used the term [[The Malay Archipelago|''Malay Archipelago'']] as the title of his influential book documenting his studies in the region. He proposed what would come to be known as the \"[[Wallace Line]]\", a boundary that separated the flora and fauna of Asia and Australia. The ice age boundary was formed by the deep water straits between [[Borneo]] and [[Sulawesi]]; and through the [[Lombok Strait]] between [[Bali]] and [[Lombok]]. This is now considered the western border of the [[Wallacea]] transition zone between the [[Ecozone|zoogeographical regions]] of Asia and Australia. The zone has a mixture of species of Asian and Australian origin, and its own endemic species.\n\n== Demography ==\n{{See also|Southeast Asia#Demographics}}\n\nOver 380 million people live in the region, with the 10 most populated islands being the following:\n\n# [[Java]] (141,000,000)\n# [[Sumatra]] (50,180,000)\n# [[Luzon]] (48,520,774)\n# [[Mindanao]] (21,902,000)\n# [[Borneo]] (21,258,000)\n# [[Sulawesi]] (21,258,000)\n# [[New Guinea]] (11,306,940)\n# [[Singapore]] (5,638,700)\n# [[Negros Island|Negros]] (4,414,131)\n# [[Panay]] (4,302,634)\n\nThe people living there are predominantly from [[Austronesian peoples|Austronesian]] sub-groupings and correspondingly speak western [[Malayo-Polynesian languages]]. The main religions in this region are [[Islam]], [[Christianity]], [[Buddhism]], [[Hinduism]] and traditional [[animism]].\n\nCulturally, the region is often seen{{Who|date=June 2011}} as part of \"Farther India\" or [[Greater India]]\u2014the Coedes' ''Indianized states of Southeast Asia'' refers to it as \"Island Southeast Asia\".<ref>Coedes, G. (1968) ''The Indianized states of Southeast Asia'' Edited by Walter F. Vella. Translated by Susan Brown Cowing.Canberra : Australian National University Press. Introduction... ''The geographic area here called ''Farther India'' consists of Indonesia, or island Southeast Asia....''</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col|small=yes}}\n*[[Greater Indonesia]]\n*[[Insulindia]]\n*[[Malay Peninsula]]\n*[[Malayness]]\n*[[Maphilindo]]\n*[[Maritime Southeast Asia]]\n*[[Nusantara]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [[Alfred Russel Wallace|Wallace, Alfred Russel]]. ''The Malay Archipelago'', [http://www.authorama.com/book/malay-archipelago-1.html Volume I], [http://www.authorama.com/book/malay-archipelago-2.html, Volume II].\n* [http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15324coll10/id/42850/rec/1 Art of Island Southeast Asia], full-text of an exhibition catalog from the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\n\n{{Countries of the Malay Archipelago}}\n{{Regions of the world}}\n\n[[Category:Malaya| 01]]\n[[Category:Islands of Southeast Asia]]\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Southeast Asia]]\n[[Category:Maritime Southeast Asia|*]]\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of the Indian Ocean]]\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:International archipelagoes]]\n", "name_user": "Xindeho", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malay_Archipelago"}
{"title_page": "Richard Currie", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian businessman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n'''Richard James Currie''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|OC}} (born 1937 in [[Saint John, New Brunswick]]) is a Canadian businessman.\n\n== Education ==\nHe entered the [[University of New Brunswick]] in 1955 on a [[Beaverbrook Scholarship]] and was elected president of the first-year class.<ref name=chancellor>[https://www.unb.ca/news/view.cgi?id=210 \"Richard Currie named chancellor of the University of New Brunswick\"], ''[[University of New Brunswick]]'', retrieved June 14, 2006</ref> He later received a [[Bachelor of Engineering]] in Chemistry degree from the [[Technical University of Nova Scotia]] in 1960. He worked as an engineer until 1968, when he entered [[Harvard University]] to earn a [[Master of Business Administration]] degree in 1970.<ref>[http://www.canadianbusiness.com/lifestyle/article.jsp?content=20050411_66891_66891 \"Live and Learn: Richard Currie\"], ''[[Canadian Business]]'', retrieved August 16, 2006.</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1960, he joined Atlantic Sugar Refineries as a Process Engineer and was a Refining Superintendent from 1963 to 1968. After graduating from Harvard in 1970, he became a Senior Associate at [[McKinsey & Company|McKinsey & Co.]], a management consultant firm based in [[New York City]].<ref name=CBR>[http://www.cbr.ca/personProfile.aspx?personID=29775 \"Executive Profiles: Richard J. Currie\"], ''[[Canadian Business Resource]]'', retrieved August 25, 2006.</ref>\n\nIn 1972, he joined [[Loblaws]] as a Vice-President, becoming Executive Vice-President in 1974, and President in 1976. Loblaws increased its market share over 350 times in 25 years while under his control, reaching $14 billion before he stepped down on December 31, 2000.<ref name=\"chancellor\"/><ref name=CBR/> Through this, it became the largest private sector employer in Canada.<ref name=\"chancellor\"/>\n\nIn 1996, he was appointed President of Loblaws parent company, [[George Weston Ltd.]], where he increased the share price from $16 to $123. In 2002 he stepped down from Weston and was appointed Chairman of [[BCE Inc.]] on April 24 of that year.<ref name=\"chancellor\"/><ref name=CBR/>\n\nHe, along with Lynton Wilson, [[Anthony S. Fell]], [[James Fleck]], [[Hal Jackman]] and John McArthur, helped establish a chair in Canadian business history at the [[Rotman School of Management|Joseph L. Rotman School of Management]], which is the first chair of its kind in Canada. Worth $3 million, it will help fund courses and research related to the progress of the commerce industry in Canada, along with the legal, economic and political events that impacted its history.<ref>[http://www.research.utoronto.ca/edge/fall2004/upfront.html \"$3M Business History Chair a First in Canada\"], ''EDGE Magazine'', retrieved August 25, 2006.</ref>\n\nHe was the Chairman of BCE Inc. and Bell Canada from 2002 to 2009 and currently sits on the [[board of directors]] of [[CAE (company)|CAE]], and [[Staples, Inc.]] and is also a Trustee of The Art Gallery of Ontario and a Director of Historical Foundation of Canada. Along with these titles, he is also Chairman of the Board of Telesat and was a Director of Imperial Oil Limited, and a member of the International Advisory Boards of RJR Nabisco and Jacobs Suchard.<ref name=CBR/>\n\n== University of New Brunswick involvement ==\nOn May 24, 2003, he was appointed Chancellor of the University of New Brunswick by the lieutenant-governor in council, at UNB's 174th Encaenia. His duties are to serve as the honorary head of UNB and also as a member of its Board of Governors.<ref name=chancellor />\n\nIn 2004, he established the [[Blake-Kirkpatrick Scholarship]]s (now the Currie Scholarship) in memory of his two grandmothers: Ida Mae Blake and Jannet Kirkpatrick.<ref>[https://www.unb.ca/scholarships/documents/BlakeKirkpatrick06.pdf \"Blake-Kirkpatrick Application\"], ''[[University of New Brunswick]]'', retrieved August 25, 2006.</ref>\n\nOn October 20, 2005, the University of New Brunswick established a Chair in Nanotechnology in his honour. This is the first Chair in Nanotechnology in Canada.<ref>[https://www.unb.ca/news/view.cgi?id=869 \"Chair in nanotechnology establish in honour of UNB chancellor\"], John Suart, ''[[University of New Brunswick]]'', October 20, 2005, retrieved August 25, 2006.</ref>\n\nIn Fall 2011 work was completed on the Richard J. Currie Center, a five-storey, 139,000-square-foot athletics and gymnasium complex, named in honor of Currie, who was also the primary donor.  Currie donated over $20 million toward the construction of the building, the largest single donation a New Brunswick university has ever received.<ref>[https://www.unb.ca/fredericton/currie/ \"The Richard J. Currie Center @ UNB Fredericton\"], ''[[University of New Brunswick]]'', retrieved October 16, 2011.</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n*1997, Made a Member of the [[Order of Canada]] \n*1997, [[Distinguished Canadian Retailer of the Year|Distinguished Canadian Retailer of the Year Award]]\n*2001, Awarded Canada's Outstanding CEO of the Year\n*2004, Promoted to Officer of the Order of Canada \n*2005, Awarded [[Retail Council of Canada|Retail Council of Canada's]] [[Retail Council of Canada's Lifetime Achievement Award|Lifetime Achievement Award]]\n*Inducted into the Canadian Business Hall of Fame <ref name=chancellor/>\n*2010, Awarded Doctor of Letters as an honorary degree from Dalhousie University, Nova Scotia\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Bell Canada}}\n{{CAE}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Currie, Richard}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Bell Canada]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Saint John, New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Canadian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Canadian university and college chancellors]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:McKinsey & Company people]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:University of New Brunswick alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian businessman|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n'''Richard James Currie''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|OC}} (born 1937 in [[Saint John, New Brunswick]]) is a Canadian businessman.\n\n== Education ==\nHe entered the [[University of New Brunswick]] in 1955 on a [[Beaverbrook Scholarship]] and was elected president of the first-year class.<ref name=chancellor>[https://www.unb.ca/news/view.cgi?id=210 \"Richard Currie named chancellor of the University of New Brunswick\"], ''[[University of New Brunswick]]'', retrieved June 14, 2006</ref> He later received a [[Bachelor of Engineering]] in Chemistry degree from the [[Technical University of Nova Scotia]] in 1960. He worked as an engineer until 1968, when he entered [[Harvard University]] to earn a [[Masters of Business Administration]] degree in 1970.<ref>[http://www.canadianbusiness.com/lifestyle/article.jsp?content=20050411_66891_66891 \"Live and Learn: Richard Currie\"], ''[[Canadian Business]]'', retrieved August 16, 2006.</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1960, he joined Atlantic Sugar Refineries as a Process Engineer and was a Refining Superintendent from 1963 to 1968. After graduating from Harvard in 1970, he became a Senior Associate at [[McKinsey & Company|McKinsey & Co.]], a management consultant firm based in [[New York City]].<ref name=CBR>[http://www.cbr.ca/personProfile.aspx?personID=29775 \"Executive Profiles: Richard J. Currie\"], ''[[Canadian Business Resource]]'', retrieved August 25, 2006.</ref>\n\nIn 1972, he joined [[Loblaws]] as a Vice-President, becoming Executive Vice-President in 1974, and President in 1976. Loblaws increased its market share over 350 times in 25 years while under his control, reaching $14 billion before he stepped down on December 31, 2000.<ref name=\"chancellor\"/><ref name=CBR/> Through this, it became the largest private sector employer in Canada.<ref name=\"chancellor\"/>\n\nIn 1996, he was appointed President of Loblaws parent company, [[George Weston Ltd.]], where he increased the share price from $16 to $123. In 2002 he stepped down from Weston and was appointed Chairman of [[BCE Inc.]] on April 24 of that year.<ref name=\"chancellor\"/><ref name=CBR/>\n\nHe, along with Lynton Wilson, [[Anthony S. Fell]], [[James Fleck]], [[Hal Jackman]] and John McArthur, helped establish a chair in Canadian business history at the [[Rotman School of Management|Joseph L. Rotman School of Management]], which is the first chair of its kind in Canada. Worth $3 million, it will help fund courses and research related to the progress of the commerce industry in Canada, along with the legal, economic and political events that impacted its history.<ref>[http://www.research.utoronto.ca/edge/fall2004/upfront.html \"$3M Business History Chair a First in Canada\"], ''EDGE Magazine'', retrieved August 25, 2006.</ref>\n\nHe was the Chairman of BCE Inc. and Bell Canada from 2002 to 2009 and currently sits on the [[board of directors]] of [[CAE (company)|CAE]], and [[Staples, Inc.]] and is also a Trustee of The Art Gallery of Ontario and a Director of Historical Foundation of Canada. Along with these titles, he is also Chairman of the Board of Telesat and was a Director of Imperial Oil Limited, and a member of the International Advisory Boards of RJR Nabisco and Jacobs Suchard.<ref name=CBR/>\n\n== University of New Brunswick involvement ==\nOn May 24, 2003, he was appointed Chancellor of the University of New Brunswick by the lieutenant-governor in council, at UNB's 174th Encaenia. His duties are to serve as the honorary head of UNB and also as a member of its Board of Governors.<ref name=chancellor />\n\nIn 2004, he established the [[Blake-Kirkpatrick Scholarship]]s (now the Currie Scholarship) in memory of his two grandmothers: Ida Mae Blake and Jannet Kirkpatrick.<ref>[https://www.unb.ca/scholarships/documents/BlakeKirkpatrick06.pdf \"Blake-Kirkpatrick Application\"], ''[[University of New Brunswick]]'', retrieved August 25, 2006.</ref>\n\nOn October 20, 2005, the University of New Brunswick established a Chair in Nanotechnology in his honour. This is the first Chair in Nanotechnology in Canada.<ref>[https://www.unb.ca/news/view.cgi?id=869 \"Chair in nanotechnology establish in honour of UNB chancellor\"], John Suart, ''[[University of New Brunswick]]'', October 20, 2005, retrieved August 25, 2006.</ref>\n\nIn Fall 2011 work was completed on the Richard J. Currie Center, a five-storey, 139,000-square-foot athletics and gymnasium complex, named in honor of Currie, who was also the primary donor.  Currie donated over $20 million toward the construction of the building, the largest single donation a New Brunswick university has ever received.<ref>[https://www.unb.ca/fredericton/currie/ \"The Richard J. Currie Center @ UNB Fredericton\"], ''[[University of New Brunswick]]'', retrieved October 16, 2011.</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n*1997, Made a Member of the [[Order of Canada]] \n*1997, [[Distinguished Canadian Retailer of the Year|Distinguished Canadian Retailer of the Year Award]]\n*2001, Awarded Canada\u2019s Outstanding CEO of the Year\n*2004, Promoted to Officer of the Order of Canada \n*2005, Awarded [[Retail Council of Canada|Retail Council of Canada's]] [[Retail Council of Canada's Lifetime Achievement Award|Lifetime Achievement Award]]\n*Inducted into the Canadian Business Hall of Fame <ref name=chancellor/>\n*2010, Awarded Doctor of Letters as an honorary degree from Dalhousie University, Nova Scotia\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Bell Canada}}\n{{CAE}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Currie, Richard}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Bell Canada]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Saint John, New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Canadian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Canadian university and college chancellors]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:McKinsey & Company people]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:University of 